- cs.SE (Software Engineering) is the most likely category as the paper focuses on the activities of developers in open-source projects and their impact on project outcomes, which is a key aspect of software engineering.
- cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is also likely as the paper analyzes the communicative and supportive activities of elite developers in open-source projects, which can be seen as a form of social networking.
- cs.CY (Computers and Society) is a possible category as the paper discusses the implications of the results for supporting elite developers, which can be seen as a societal issue.
- cs.SD (Software Development and Programming) is another possible category as the paper analyzes the contributions of developers in open-source projects, which is a key aspect of software development.
- cs.PL (Programming Languages) is a less likely category as the paper does not focus on programming languages specifically, but rather on the activities of developers in open-source projects.
